Talks Held between Kim Yong Nam and Wu Bangguo 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Beijing, October 18 (KCNA Correspondent) -- Talks were held between Kim Yong Nam, president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, and Wu Bangguo, chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress of the People's Republic of China, at the Great Hall of the People Monday.
 At the talks the two sides informed each other of their countries' situation and exchanged views on the issue of further boosting the friendly and cooperative relations between the two countries in the new century and a series of international matters of mutual concern and reached a consensus of views on the issues taken up. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK side noted with high appreciation that the new collective leadership of China headed by Hu Jintao was attaching great importance to the development of the DPRK-China friendly relations and clarified once again the stand of the Workers' Party of Korea and the DPRK government to make energetic efforts together with the Chinese comrades to lift the relations to a new stage. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK side congratulated the Chinese people on the successes they had gained in socialist modernization with Chinese characteristics and wished them greater advance in the drive to build a comprehensively well-off society and achieve the country's reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Referring to the fact that under the Songun leadership of Kim Jong Il the army and people of the DPRK were defending the dignity and sovereignty of the country and gains of socialism and accelerating the building of a great prosperous powerful nation, single-heartedly united around the headquarters of the revolution, the DPRK side expressed the unshakable will to realize the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula by finding a peaceful solution to the nuclear issue and achieve the independent reunification of the country through national cooperation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Chinese side said it was of great importance in further developing the Sino-Korean friendly relations in the new century to mark the 55th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations between China and the DPRK and, in particular, several China visits by Kim Jong Il in recent years had served as a good foundation for the development of the bilateral relations. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Chinese side underscored the need to further develop the Sino-Korean friendly and cooperative relations in various fields in the new century. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Chinese side said it was pleased to note that the Korean people were registering successes, overcoming difficulties in the spirit of self-reliance and fortitude under the leadership of the WPK headed by Kim Jong Il, and expressed support to the positive efforts of the DPRK side for a peaceful solution to the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present at the talks on the DPRK side were members of the delegation Ri Ju O, minister of Light Industry, Kim Yong Il, vice-minister of Foreign Affairs, Kim Yong Jae, vice-minister of Foreign Trade, Choe Jin Su, DPRK ambassador e.p. to China, and suite members. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present on the Chinese side were Minister of Commerce Bo Xilai, Deputy Secretary General of the NPC Standing Committee Wang Yunlong, Chinese Ambassador e.p. to the DPRK Wu Donghe, Vice-Chairman of the Foreign Affairs Committee of the NPC Wang Yingfan, Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Zhou Wenzhong, and officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The talks proceeded in a sincere and friendly atmosphere.

DPRK Delegation Visits Zhong Guancun Scientific and Technological Complex 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Beijing, October 18 (KCNA Correspondent) -- The DPRK delegation led by Kim Yong Nam, president of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, on an official goodwill visit to China visited the Zhong Guancun Scientific and Technological Complex in Beijing Monday afternoon.
 He went there together with Minister of Light Industry Ri Ju O, Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Kim Yong Il, Vice-Minister of Foreign Trade Kim Yong Jae, DPRK Ambassador E.P. to China Choe Jin Su, who are members of the delegation and other suite members. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They were accompanied by Chinese Ambassador E.P. to the DPRK Wu Donghe and officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Being briefed on the fact that as China's centre for scientific and technological researches this complex has contributed to the development of up-to-date science and technology and training able scientists and technicians, they acquainted themselves with the achievements made by it in researches into information science and technology.

DPRK Delegation Visits Chinese Village 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Beijing, October 19 (KCNA Correspondent) -- The DPRK delegation headed by President Kim Yong Nam of the Presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly on an official goodwill visit to the People's Republic of China (PRC) visited modern village Han Cun He Cun in Fang Shan District in a suburb of Beijing on Tuesday.
 Kim Yong Nam went there together with members of the delegation - Light Industry Minister Ri Ju O, Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs Kim Yong Il, Vice-Minister of Foreign Trade Kim Yong Jae and DPRK Ambassador e.p. to China Choe Jin Su -- and other suite members. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The delegation was accompanied by Chinese Ambassador e.p. to the DPRK Wu Donghe and other Chinese officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The visitors were greeted by senior officials of the district and village. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At the room devoted to the history of the village, they were briefed on the fact that the village has improved the standard of its inhabitants by developing economy with main emphasis on agriculture and construction. Then they went round with keen interest dwelling houses, a vegetable greenhouse and other places.

Women's Group for Abolition of SL Formed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 19 (KCNA) -- The Women's Group for Actions for the Abolition of the Security Law (SL) was reportedly formed in Seoul on Oct. 13 by women's organizations including the National Federation of Woman-Peasants Associations, the National Council of Girl Student Representatives, the Anti-U.S. Women's Society, the Women's Society for Reunification and the Women's Committee of the south Korean Confederation of Trade Unions.
 A resolution titled "Let's totally abolish the SL and advance towards independent reunification" was read out at the inaugural ceremony of the group. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Accusing the conservative forces including the Grand National Party of making last-ditch efforts to maintain the SL though there is no justification to keep it in force any longer after the publication of the June 15 joint declaration, the resolution terms them foolish and brazen-faced moves to stem the trend of history. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
It went on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The ruling party's talk about "alternative legislation and supplement to the criminal law" is nothing but a scheme to keep the north listed as an "anti-state organization," perpetuate the national division and escalate the confrontation, going against the people's desire and demand of the times for the abolition of the SL. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It called on the women to courageously come out to carry out the historic task for the repeal of the SL irrespective of their differing positions and conditions.

Exhibition of S. Korean Artists for Abolition of SL Opens 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 19 (KCNA) -- An exhibition of south Korean artists for the abolition of the "Security Law" reportedly opened in Seoul on October 15.
 Secretary General of the Cultural Solidarity Ji Kum Jong and other speakers said at its opening ceremony that the SL was an evil law against democracy and human rights and, at the same time, a law restricting the imagination and creative capacity of the artists and that they would lay a springboard for tearing up the SL with the exhibition as the starting point. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The exhibition will be open till October 23. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Meanwhile, an image festival for the abolition of the SL opened there.

S. Korean Uri Party-Proposed "Amendment to Criminal Law" Denounced 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, October 19 (KCNA) -- The ruling Uri Party of south Korea proposed an "amendment to the criminal law" as a bill related to the issue of abolishing the "Security Law" on October 17.
 Rodong Sinmun Tuesday in a signed commentary terms this bill the second SL and an evil law against reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The commentary says: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The bill, in fact, calls for keeping the core of the SL, its main poisonous articles as they are because this bill includes the clause on the "organization aimed at internal disturbance" little different from the provisions on the "anti-state organization," "enemy-benefiting organization." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The bill is, in the final analysis, a version of the SL. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 For the Uri Party to propose such a bill is an unpardonable crime against democracy and reunification as it goes against the trend of the reunification era after the publication of the June 15 joint declaration, defying the mind-set of the south Korean people towards democracy, human rights and independent reunification and currying favor with the Grand National Party. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Uri Party has so far talked a lot about "political reforms" and the abolition of the "SL" but, in fact, played tricks contrary to the expectation of the nation, pursuing quite different aims. The party adopted the abolition of the "SL" as its policy and pushed forward the move for legislation on it. This was done not prompted by any political creed but by opportunist self-protectionism. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 If any new law in south Korea contains even a single clause of the SL, this will make it impossible to improve the inter-Korean relations and achieve the genuine democratization of the society and human rights, the desires of the south Korean people.

